the First Voices, First Texts series, which publishes lost or under appreciated texts by Indigenous writers. This reissue of Mini Aodla Freeman’s path-breaking work includes new material, an interview with the author, and an afterword by Keavy Martin and Julie Rak, with Norma Dunning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Native Americans.2bisacsh  aDepartment of Indian and Northern Affairs.  aInuit.  aJames Bay.  aOttawa.  aautobiography.  atuberculosis.1 aDunning, Norma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Keavy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Keavy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRak, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRak, Julie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755492640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887554926423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887554926/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles